notes.p: Mary returned from her first birding class talking about this bird, calling it Disney-like; the hunched-over posture, the gleaming red eye. We first decided to purchase binoculars on an early outing when we couldn't distinguish between a night heron and a styrofoam meat tray.

family.common-name: Partridges, Grouse, Turkeys, and Old World Quail

notes.p: A fully-inflated Male Sage Grouse on its Lek is perhaps the craziest-looking bird I've ever seen. Amazing.

Adult Coots are very familiar to us in the San Francisco Bay Area, but the chicks with their fuzzy orange hairdos are still fascinating to watch. We also now watch for the draconian way the parents drive off their weaker offspring.
I added the abbreviation DOWITCH to this Genus record to denote the fact that we can't always tell the difference between the two dowitchers we see out here.

subfamily.common-name: New World Parakeets, Macaws and Parrots

notes.p: Bushtits pass among our trees every morning, chittering overhead while I go out to collect the newspaper.
Towhee's often visit our backyard, giving their loud, percussive call note and scratching around on the grass and cement.
see also Dark-eyed Junco; it's likely that there's no meaningful distinction in our pre-2001 records between daejun and orejun.
When I began recording sightings, Bullock's and Baltimore Oriole were one species; I have changed my original notation of 'norori' for 11/1997 to 'bulori' based on probable range of each species.
